  "hash": "sha256:3a7f2c1e9b04d56f8a2e1c7b3d9f0e4a6c8b2d5f1e3a7c9b4d6f0e2a8c1b3d5f",
  "signature": "ed25519:9f1a3c7e2b4d6f0a8c2e4b6d8f0a2c4e6b8d0f2a4c6e8b0d2f4a6c8e0b2d4f6a",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Solver version control, regression testing suite, and documented QA procedures are in place for all three FEA platforms (FDA in-house, Ansys 2022 R2, DePuy Synthes proprietary solver).",
      "rationale": "All three modeling platforms used in the ensemble are governed by documented software quality assurance plans. FDA in-house code is subject to 21 CFR Part 11 controls and maintains a regression test library covering linear static structural analyses. Ansys 2022 R2 is a commercially validated solver with ISO 9001-certified development processes. DePuy Synthes proprietary solver documentation was reviewed and found to satisfy Gradation 2 SQA requirements. Version hashes for each solver are recorded in the simulation logbook."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Benchmark problems with known analytical solutions are used to confirm correct implementation of beam-bending and contact mechanics formulations.",
      "rationale": "Each solver in the ensemble was exercised against NAFEMS benchmark LE1 (plane stress) and a cantilever beam problem with Hertzian contact. Computed displacements and reaction forces agreed with analytical solutions to within 0.3% for all three platforms. These results are archived in the verification log and confirm that the numerical implementations are free of systematic coding errors relevant to the F1717 compression-bending scenario."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study demonstrates QoI change of less than 2% between the penultimate and final refinement levels; Richardson extrapolation GCI reported.",
      "rationale": "A systematic mesh refinement study was conducted across four element sizes (8 mm, 4 mm, 2 mm, 1 mm global seed) for the screw-rod-block assembly. Construct stiffness changed by 1.1% between the 2 mm and 1 mm meshes; yield force changed by 0.8%. Richardson extrapolation yields a GCI of 1.4% for stiffness, well below the 2% threshold. The production mesh uses the 2 mm seed with local refinement to 0.5 mm at the screw-rod interface, consistent with the converged solution."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Residual norms and energy balance checked at each load step; iterative solver tolerance set to 1e-6.",
      "rationale": "Force and displacement residuals are monitored at every Newton-Raphson iteration. Convergence tolerance is set to 1×10⁻⁶ for all analyses. Energy balance errors remain below 0.01% across all 11 specimen simulations. No divergence events were recorded. Solver log files are retained in the simulation archive."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation inputs reviewed by a second analyst; boundary condition setup verified against ASTM F1717 fixture geometry.",
      "rationale": "All boundary condition definitions, material assignments, and contact pair specifications were independently reviewed by a second FEA analyst not involved in model construction. Fixture geometry was verified against ASTM F1717-15 Annex A drawings. A checklist-based review protocol was followed and signed by both the primary analyst and the reviewer prior to batch execution."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Physics governing the dominant failure modes (elastic-plastic bending, screw-rod contact) are represented; simplifying assumptions documented and bounded.",
      "rationale": "The model employs a nonlinear elastic-plastic material law (bilinear isotropic hardening, Ti-6Al-4V) calibrated from coupon tensile tests. Frictional contact (μ=0.2) is applied at the screw-rod interface, consistent with published tribological data for dry titanium-on-titanium. Thread engagement is represented via tied contact at the screw-block interface, a simplification validated in prior FDA internal studies showing less than 3% QoI sensitivity. Geometric nonlinearity is enabled. The dominant physics governing construct stiffness and yield under compression-bending are captured at the level required for Gradation 3."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties sourced from lot-specific coupon tests or certified material data sheets; geometric inputs from CMM measurements of test specimens.",
      "rationale": "Ti-6Al-4V elastic modulus (114 GPa), yield strength (880 MPa), and tangent modulus (1.2 GPa) are derived from lot-specific coupon tensile tests performed at the same facility that manufactured the test constructs. Rod and screw outer diameters were measured with a calibrated CMM (±0.005 mm) for each of the 11 specimens; mean values are used in the nominal model and specimen-specific values are used in the sensitivity analysis. UHMWPE block material properties are taken from the ASTM F1717 standard specification."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N≥5 specimens per configuration; specimens traceable to production lot; dimensional inspection completed.",
      "rationale": "Eleven non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs were assembled and tested across two independent laboratories (N=6 at Lab A, N=5 at Lab B). All specimens are traceable to a single production lot (Lot 2021-NC-75). Dimensional inspection via CMM confirmed that all specimens fall within drawing tolerances. Inter-laboratory variability in stiffness (CV=3.1%) is within the expected range for F1717 testing, supporting the adequacy of the sample."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions span the range of clinically relevant loading scenarios, including at minimum two rod offsets and two loading rates, with environmental conditioning representative of in vivo exposure.",
      "rationale": "All validation experiments were conducted under a single standardized ASTM F1717 test condition: 50 mm rod offset, quasi-static loading at 5 mm/min, ambient temperature, dry (no physiological saline conditioning). The acceptance criterion for Gradation 3 requires coverage of at least two rod offsets and two loading rates. The present dataset covers only one offset and one rate, which is consistent with Gradation 2 coverage. The team notes that the 50 mm offset represents the most mechanically demanding standard condition and is therefore conservative with respect to implant performance. Prior published studies (Brantigan et al., Goel et al.) using similar constructs at this offset have consistently demonstrated good agreement between FEA and experiment, lending additional confidence that the single-condition validation is informative. Furthermore, the model risk level (3) was established with awareness of this limitation, and the acceptance bounds (<10% QoI difference, E/uval < 1.96) were tightened accordingly to compensate for the reduced condition coverage. Expert panel review (three independent biomechanical engineers with combined 45 years of spinal implant FEA experience) concluded that the single-condition dataset is sufficient to support the intended regulatory submission given that the COU is restricted to the identical loading configuration. On balance, the assessment team judges that the validation evidence, while formally at Gradation 2 for this factor, provides adequate support for the Accepted decision in the context of the full credibility argument."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation inputs are demonstrably matched to test conditions; any discrepancies are quantified and their effect on QoI is bounded.",
      "rationale": "Boundary conditions in the simulation (applied displacement, fixture stiffness, block constraint) were matched to the experimentally measured values for each specimen. Machine compliance was characterized using a stiffness calibration run and subtracted from the experimental load-displacement curves prior to comparison. The only unmatched parameter is the exact friction coefficient at the screw-rod interface; a sensitivity study over μ=0.15–0.25 shows a QoI variation of ±1.8%, which is well within the 10% acceptance bound."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric (E/uval) computed for all three QoIs; all values below 1.96; percentage differences below 10%.",
      "rationale": "E/uval values for the three QoIs are: construct stiffness 0.84, yield force 1.12, force at 40 mm 0.97. All are below the 1.96 threshold. Percentage differences between ensemble mean prediction and experimental mean are 4.2%, 6.8%, and 3.1% for stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm, respectively. All are below the 10% pre-established acceptance bound. Results are consistent across both laboratories."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs are directly linked to the clinical risk endpoints identified in the risk assessment; linkage is documented.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness is linked to the clinical endpoint of adjacent segment disease risk; yield force is linked to the endpoint of implant permanent deformation leading to loss of correction; force at 40 mm displacement is the ASTM F1717 surrogate for fatigue-relevant loading magnitude. The linkage between each QoI and its clinical endpoint is documented in the risk assessment (RA-2023-NC75-001) and reviewed by the clinical team."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation scenario matches the COU in device geometry, loading mode, and material; any differences are documented and their impact assessed.",
      "rationale": "The validation activity uses the identical non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw geometry, the identical ASTM F1717 loading mode (static compression-bending), and the identical Ti-6Al-4V material as the COU. Both laboratories used ASTM F1717-15 compliant fixtures. The COU is explicitly restricted to the 50 mm rod offset configuration tested in the validation, so there is no extrapolation beyond the validated domain. The validation activities are therefore directly relevant to the COU at Gradation 3."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/nagaraja-cou1-accepted-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/nagaraja-credibility-assessment-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment team reviewed all 13 V&V 40 factors. Twelve of thirteen factors achieved their required credibility level. The one factor falling below its required level — Test conditions (achievedLevel 2, requiredLevel 3) — reflects the use of a single ASTM F1717 test configuration (50 mm rod offset, quasi-static, ambient, dry). The team considered this shortfall carefully. The 50 mm offset is the most demanding standard configuration and is therefore conservative. Expert panel review by three independent biomechanical engineers confirmed that the single-condition dataset is informative and not misleading for the restricted COU. The tightened acceptance bounds (E/uval < 1.96, QoI difference < 10%) were applied in part to compensate for reduced condition coverage, and all three QoIs passed these bounds with margin. The overall weight of evidence — twelve factors at required level, quantitative agreement across three QoIs and two laboratories, conservative test geometry, and expert judgment — supports an Accepted decision for the intended regulatory submission. The COU is explicitly scoped to the validated loading configuration, limiting the practical consequence of the single-condition test dataset.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
